metadata.name: Balancium #466
metadata.description:
"Balancium" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022

In the fall of 1931, in Alexander Calder's studio, Marcel Duchamp coined the term 'mobile' for his kinetic sculptures. Later, Calder wrote: "This, in French, means not only 'movable'â€” but also a 'motive', 'a reason for an act' so I found it a very good word."
 
Around the same year, Bruno Munari started making colorful and whimsical mobiles. He called them "useless machines", existing without any purpose and inviting viewers to just look. Elements are connected with nearly invisible threads or wires, allowing the artist to create the illusion of shapes floating in the air.

Balancium is both a virtual mobile and a useless object. Generated by the code, it undergoes a continual transformation. The movement of the air, or invisible fluid, becomes an integral part of the design and amplifies serenity. 
 
There is a keyboard key that unlocks more variations.

metadata.name: Bored Computer Screen #458
metadata.description:
"Bored Computer Screen" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022


Bored Computer Screen (BCS) is a direct descendant of SpecterðŸ‘»pixelâ¬›latteâ˜•, where the central idea is agent and displacement. In BCS, there are agentsâ€”the small moving circlesâ€”that get their colors ripped away by the surrounding pixels. Though they occur on the same screen space, they are separated in their own cells, a simultaneous multiverse of sorts. In some iterations, a very clear voronoi pattern will appear. I didn't consciously strive for this look. It's what naturally happens, when you try to divide space, so that the borders occur exactly in between the closest neighbor. When I first saw this pattern emerge, I wanted to see how far I could get the distinct cells to influence each other. The idea that the same algorithmic processes can happen many times but still separately in a single piece has always interested me (and explored in the Infinite Browse series). BCS is an extension of that, albeit a little more chaotic.

Note:
- Best experience on browsers and devices with support for WebGL2 

Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao) with P5, P5Fbo and perlinjs.

metadata.name: Geometric city #9
metadata.description:
Typical cities are grey, depressing, and sometimes stressful. This collection is an image of a utopian city where buildings are shamelessly colorful, and happiness is widespread. Nothing would be more appropriate to celebrate the birthday of everyoneâ€™s favorite generative art platform, fx(hash). 
Special thanks to Ida Belle for her help with the English description. 
 
This artwork has 6 major traits. I've mentioned these traits below: 
 
 Trait 1: This code contains 23 unique colors for the building and the base (block) Plus 18 different colors for lightning. The different lighting makes the color palette more diverse. 
 
Trait 2: 4 different views of the city. 
 
Trait 3 : 3 types of strokes in geometric shapes. 
 
Trait 4: 8 levels for density of buildings 
 
Trait 5: 7 levels for the size of the city blocks. 
 
Trait 6: 7 different types of buildings. In this town, the buildings are of geometric shapes. 
 
15% of primary sell donate to processing foundation.

metadata.name: Living Squares Study II #12
metadata.description:
1024x1024 generative animation (Vanilla JS canvas)

This piece is an evolving painting. Press "s" to download a png file on live.
In this world of rotating squares they try to find a place and interact with each other.
The squares can have a fixed number of divisions or can grow with size.
An optional feature generates lines in the background when they collide.
There are a much more other features.
Wait and see how the painting evolves, you can click or touch to toggle the animation.


12 features included

36 Color palettes
Number of squares (between 2 and 12)
Dashing pixels and linewidth
Stripe width (narrow, normal, thick)
Skew (true or false)
Number of square divisions
Rotation Speed
Rotation Direction
Opacity 
Background lines

Daniel JuliÃ 
December 2021

metadata.name: Jarapa Generator #28
metadata.description:
Generative canvas Vanilla JS 1024x1024px

A jarapa is a thick fabric of diverse composition, used to make cheap rugs and blankets, usually with imperfections, very common in the Mediterranean basin, especially in Spain.
My mother used to put them everywhere.
Originally, jarapas were brightly colored rugs that were made on familiar artisan looms from wool scraps or old rags, or waste from textile industries.
(Source https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jarapa)
In this algorithm there are several internal features related to the fabric creation.
There 2 main techniques (wool scraps or rags)

Features include 

- Wool colors
- Used technique
- Stripes direction 
- Imperfections (100% perfect is very rare)
- Internal numbers related to the algorithm, Rounds, Depth and Steps

Click "s" to download a screenshot

Daniel JuliÃ 
December 2021

metadata.name: BINARY WORDS #272
metadata.description:
I drew my first 8x8 pixel binary image on 11/08/2022 with 'iloveyou' encoded for my wife, it was our 10-year anniversary on this day.  After that made this generative stuff for fxhash's birthday bash.

#fxhashturnsone

Donations:
25% to ThreeJs team

The image contains a binary coded word or phrase with a length of 8 characters. The grays represents 0, the other colors represents 1. One row -> one character. Should be proceed decoding from left to right and from top to bottom.

An example: 'iloveyou'

01101001
01101100
01101111
01110110
01100101
01111001
01101111
01110101

The fxrandom selects a word and the program converts it to binary data. After that, the background (ground and sky) is randomly generated from color schemes. Then the binary gray colors are drawn. Also the color of light next to null colors is randomly generated from color schemes. Random affects also the animation.

The animation stops when you do these interactions below, then restarts after a few seconds of inactivity.

Press spacebar to change:

- frame view -> without frame
- without frame -> original 8x8px size
- original 8x8px size -> frame view

Press 's' to save an svg from current view.

Notes:
- Build with ReactJs and TweenJs
- Every upcoming day, half of the remaining pieces are burned.

Happy Birthday fxhash community!
I'm glad to be among you!

metadata.name: Misunderstanding #39
metadata.description:
Each color/stripe represents a single person or a group of people, trying to communicate with each other. But their attempts in an understandable and agreeable communication are mostly always misaligned. Hence, none of them understand each other as they want to be understood. And for that, some of them don't even bother trying to communicate at all.

* * *

Happy anniversary! #fxhashturnsone

Press S to save as PNG. To save a larger image, open live view, add "&s=WIDTH_IN_PIXELS" to the end of the URL, press Enter and then press S.

Artwork by: yenren / twitter.com/yenrenART

metadata.name: Punktwelt #560
metadata.description:
Continuing on the theme of color perception in Farbteiler, Punktwelt is an exploration of color interaction, projection and perceived depth, and the aesthetics of simple Boolean operations on form.

Each shape is the result of a single block, a rectangular cuboid, subjected to a series of Boolean subtractions with other blocks, and rendered in parallel projection, oblique or axonometric, in the abstract landscape of the Punktwelt.

Some have horizons, some have banded or striped backgrounds. The unnatural drawing order and chromatic differences of the individual faces sometimes yields illusory or paradoxical visual geometries.

Press â€™sâ€™ to save a png. Press â€™4â€™ to export a high resolution png. Press â€™8â€™ to export a very high resolution png. Press â€™eâ€™ to export an SVG file (may take some time and produce large files).

Aspect ratio variations are 4:5, 5:4, 2:3, 3:2 and 1:1.

Built in Javascript with p5.js, p5.svg and csg.js.

metadata.name: Broken Symmetries #3/3 #45
metadata.description:
"I think a lot of us feel, when we look at the Dow Jones plunging, alienated - you do feel as if we're in the grip of some alien force that slipped human control."
Robert Harris

This piece is the third in a planed series of three intended as studies on composition.

It is built entirely on thi.ng/umbrella libraries and template:

https://github.com/thi-ng/fxhash-tpl

Keyboard shortcuts

- 1 : render @ original resolution
- 2 : render @ 2 x resolution
- 4 : render @ 4 x resolution
- x : download canvas as PNG @ current resolution
- s : download canvas as SVG @ current resolution; This can be used with a plotter.
